The 'instanceof' operator in Java is used to determine if an object is an instance of a particular class, a subclass of that class, or implements an interface. It returns a boolean value, either true or false, depending on whether the object belongs to the specified class or not.

It can be helpful in situations where we need to perform specific operations on an object based on its type or class. It is commonly used in polymorphism and inheritance.

Here's an example code snippet that demonstrates the usage of the 'instanceof' operator:

```
//parent class
class Animal {
   public void eat() {
      System.out.println("Animal is eating");
   }
}

//subclass
class Dog extends Animal {
   public void bark() {
      System.out.println("Dog is barking");
   }
}

//main method
public class Main {
   public static void main(String[] args) {
      Animal animal = new Animal();
      Dog dog = new Dog();

      //Checking if objects belong to a certain class
      System.out.println(animal instanceof Animal); //true
      System.out.println(dog instanceof Animal); //true

      //Checking if objects belong to a subclass
      System.out.println(dog instanceof Dog); //true
      System.out.println(animal instanceof Dog); //false

      //Using instanceof to perform specific operations
      if (animal instanceof Dog) {
         Dog d = (Dog) animal; //typecasting
         d.bark();
      }
   }
}
```

In this example, we have a parent class Animal and a subclass Dog that extends the Animal class. We define two objects, one of type Animal and one of type Dog. Then we use the 'instanceof' operator to check if these objects belong to a certain class or subclass.

In the last part of the code, we use the 'instanceof' operator to check if the animal object is an instance of the Dog class. Since it is not, the if condition fails. If we had used a Dog object instead of an Animal object, the if condition would have succeeded, and we could have performed specific operations related to the Dog class.

