    // ...implementation details...
}

public void print(Printable p) {
    System.out.println(p);
}

Document doc = new Document();
print(doc);
```

Here, the print() method can take any Printable object as a parameter, regardless of its actual class, and use it to perform printing. Since Document implements Printable, it will be accepted as a valid argument, even if it has no explicit print() method. This allows for looser coupling and more flexible design, as long as the marker interface is used consistently and meaningfully.

