The 'transient' keyword in an interface variable with a final keyword in Java is used to indicate that the variable is not part of the serialized state of an object. When an object is serialized, all its non-transient fields are written to the output stream, but the transient fields are skipped.

Here is an example of using the 'transient' keyword in an interface variable with a final keyword in Java:

```
interface MyInterface {
  final int MY_CONSTANT = 42;
  transient String myTransString = "transient string";
}
```

In the above code, the 'MY_CONSTANT' variable is declared with the 'final' keyword, which means its value cannot be changed. The 'myTransString' variable is declared with the 'transient' keyword, which means it will not be part of the serialized state of an object.

If we now create a class that implements this interface and serialize it, we can see that the 'myTransString' variable will not be included.

```
class MyClass implements MyInterface, Serializable {
  private int myInt;

  public MyClass(int myInt) {
    this.myInt = myInt;
  }

  public int getMyInt() {
    return myInt;
  }

  public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
    MyClass obj = new MyClass(10);

    // Serialize object
    FileOutputStream fileOut = new FileOutputStream("myObj.ser");
    ObjectOutputStream out = new ObjectOutputStream(fileOut);
    out.writeObject(obj);
    out.close();
    fileOut.close();

    // Deserialize object
    FileInputStream fileIn = new FileInputStream("myObj.ser");
    ObjectInputStream in = new ObjectInputStream(fileIn);
    MyClass newObj = (MyClass) in.readObject();
    in.close();
    fileIn.close();

    // Verify state
    System.out.println(newObj.getMyInt()); // Output: 10
    System.out.println(newObj.myTransString); // Output: null
  }
}
```

In the above code, we create an instance of the 'MyClass' class and serialize it to a file 'myObj.ser'. We then deserialize the object and verify its state by calling 'getMyInt()' and 'myTransString' variables. We can see that 'myTransString' is null, which means it was not part of the serialized state of the object.

